{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"43059656-932d-4bd0-9394-478a6db3371d","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically captures crash reports — no `createdump` needed.\n\n**Where to find them:**\n\n1. **`~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`** — user-level crash reports (`.ips` files)\n2. **`/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`** — system-level crash reports\n\nLook for a `.ips` file matching your process name and crash timestamp.\n\n**Quick way to find it:**\n\n```bash\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/ | head\n```\n\n**You can also use Console.app** → select \"Crash Reports\" in the sidebar to browse them with a GUI.\n\nThe `.ips` file contains the native backtrace, exception type, and faulting thread — useful for symbolication with `atos` or `llvm-symbolizer`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"98c5c9b1-00dd-423e-a855-039237d92b64","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is a general knowledge question about macOS crash reporting — I don't need to search any codebase for this.","outputTokens":276,"requestId":"2C56:219FF2:166AE77:194ADD1:69F94C42"},"id":"df9b7cd1-2436-46df-b720-9c2c53917a48","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:47:54.987Z","parentId":"5645c564-6ac2-4c62-a5a6-2b52862e8811"}
